So tonight we will cover the case of an overcall over opener's suit. 
When they bid a suit (natural)|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


at|
 
"If you have a misfit, get out as soon as possible". 

Apart from flawed opening leads and not planning at trick 1, I think the most significant source of lost matchpoints is  bidding too high on misfit hands. |
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


nt||cp|2|at|^b@2
And as Marty Bergen and many others have observed, "the best bid in bridge is raising partner's suit" 
- especially if it's a major! 

Some preliminaries:
First, we want to discuss what to do if you don't have a big fit with partner... |
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


at|

Let's start with the case where the opponents bid over your partner's opening bid and you have room at the 1 level,for Example:
   1@C   (1@D)   ?? 
At the 1-level, your bid shows about 7 points or more and is forcing for 1 round.  
In other words, if you can bid at the 1 level, you pretty much ignore the overcall. 

Example: 
1@C  (1@D)  ??   Your hand is @sKxx  @hQJ10x  @dQxxx  @cxx |
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


at|    Bid 1@H 

|cp|4|at|Note that this does NOT promise a 5 card suit, but that it DENIES the other major in this particular auction |cp|2|at|
 |
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


at|
ecolodge:  Is 7 pts the minimum you can bid with at the 1 level?|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


at|
mitche:  well, no, you can bid with fewer points (6 or so), but you should have a better suit if you do.
Example: 1@C  (1@H)   ??      @sKQxxx  @hxxx  @dxx  @cJxx   is a clear 1@S bid.|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


at|
A "free bid" at the 2-level, however, should be somewhat better.  
Most people use this bid to show 10 or more points. 

What is a "free" bid? And what do they charge if it ain't free???
(The term "free bid" dates back to the ancient days of bridge, where responder would strain to bid on the chance that opener had a very strong hand and responder wanted to make sure that opener had a chance to make a second bid. When second seat overcalls, responder is relieved of the obligation to keep the bidding open for opener to get a second shot, ...hence her bid was "free", not forced, and this was supposed to show 10+ points.) |
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


at|
Nowadays, the tendency is for players to use "negative", i.e. light free bids, which I find works at matchpoints, 
but can be self-destructive if you aren't really careful.  
More on that later.|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


nt||cp|2|at|^b@2
^*bThe Negative Double:^*n

This is probably the single most important convention in the book!

If the auction begins with a suit bid by partner and an overcall below an agreed-upon level 
(usually 2NT, but I have played negative X through 4@S), the bid is takeout for the other two suits. |
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


at|
Example: Your hand pattern is 4-2-4-3 and partner opens 1@C, overcalled by 1@H
Negtive X at the 1 level here, guarantees 4 of any unbid major. 
-- not 3, not 5 -- exactly  4!!|
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


at| 

At higher levels, the negative X may show a bad 5 card major, but enough strength to play at the level 
the negative X forces you to.  
- If opener can rebid at the 1-level, then a  negative X promises a minimum of 6 or so points; 
- If opener is forced to bid at the 2-level (e.g. in the auction 1@S  (2@D), you should have pretty nearly 8 losers
- and at the 3 level, you guarantee about 12  dummy points (assuming your partner will open random 11 point hands) |
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


at|
If your style favors sound openings, your negative X may be a bit lighter.
Example: 
1@S  (2@C)    and you have @sQx  @hJxxxx  @dKJx  @cKxx 

I would not like to bid 2NT with this collection, and I do not want to suggest that partner lead hearts, 
should she get the lead. So I double 2@C as the best alternative.  
NOTE: the only suits the negative doubler promises length in are unbid majors. Opener doesn't promise shortness in the overcalled suit. Neither does the doubler promise support for unbid minors. 
Negative doubles are designed to help you get to major suit contracts and know what you're doing!

