^*BFit-showing bids after an overcall^*n|
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


at|

There are a lot of conventions that have been invented over the decades to show the nature of responder's fit 
after an overcall. I prefer a simple agreement:
First, the best bids are raises. With 3-card support for opener's MAJOR
- a minimum raise of opener's major is competitive showing 3 card support and 5-9 points. 
Example: 
1@S  (2@C)        - @sJxx  @hxxxxx  @dKQx  @cxx   |
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


at| 
With this 9 loser hand, 2@S is plenty. 
I will not negatively double or bid 2@H here, since we have a known 8-card spade fit.
- Second, with a better hand (10+ points) and support, cue bid. 
Example:
1@H  (1@S)       - @sxxx  @hKJxx  @dKx  @cK10xx       -- bid 2@S 
The cue bid shows a hand with 3 or more card support and at most 8  losers. 
Again, remember that when you force pard to the 3 level, you need a decent hand!
The sample hand is pretty nearly minimum for this sequence.|
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


nt||cp|2|at|^b@2 
Preemptive Bids:  
If you are a strict adherent to the Law of Total Tricks (LOTT), you will jump-raise partner with 4-card support 
and 0-6 points, especially if your hand has a singleton somewhere. 
It is not necessary to bid after an overcall, so when you bid, you should have something to say, 
either strength or a fit! 
Remember that partner has another bid coming!  Reread the section on 2-level free bids. |
pg| ***** 31 ***** |


at|

Sometimes we want to make tactical underbids, and here is one of the most common situations for doing so:  
^*B"death holdings"^*n |
pg| ***** 32 ***** |


at|
Holding 3 small cards in the suit bid by your opponents isn't a great thing. 
Neither is Qxx or Jxx or even QJx -- these holdings seldom help partner win tricks.  
Until you have some idea that partner has shortness in an overcalled suit, 
don't get too frisky with the death holding -- xxx in the overcalled suit. |
pg| ***** 33 ***** |


at|

So sometimes you pass the overcall - and now, it's up to opener to do something.... 
Suppose that you are opener and the auction goes 1@S by you, 2@C overcall, pass, pass... 
There you are, wondering what to do. 
If you rebid your suit, you should have a very good 5-card suit (4 of top 5 honors) or even better, 6 of them. 
Remember, responder will strain to support your major if she has any excuse to!   
Bidding a new suit (especially an unbid major) also suggests an unbalanced hand, 
so my first  preference is the ^*Breopening double^*N.|
pg| ***** 34 ***** |


at|  
Opener reopening with X suggests a shape of 5332 and a sound opener.  
It also gives responder the chance to convert the balancing takeout double to penalties on the right hand. |
pg| ***** 35 ***** |


at| 
Opener could, of course, be 5440 or so, but the reopening X gives responder a chance to go for the jugular .. 
And as you know, I am happy to accept a 500 penalty on part-score hands or misfits. |
pg| ***** 36 ***** |


nt||cp|2|at|^b@2 

So to summarize:  
When the opponents overcall, a negative X shows 4 card support for unbid majors; 
At the 2 level, you should still expect just 4 card support for unbid majors.  
We raise opener's major suit whenever we can do so, because it helps opener decide whether to bid, pass, or double. 


